September 2020 Limb Pick Up
The City of Mayfield's Public Works Department has scheduled their next limb pick-up as follows:

Dividing Line - Broadway
South Side, August 31-September 3
North Side, September 8-September 10

Please note that pick-up days are Monday through Thursday. Neighborhoods from Erwin Drive going West to Old Dublin Road, place your limbs by the curb 48 hours prior to Monday, August 31, 2020.

Be aware that items cannot be placed by the curb for removal more than 48 hours before the scheduled pickup. No items may block a sidewalk. This pick-up program is intended for limbs only. If you have a tree trimmed or cut down by a contractor, it is your or their responsibility to remove the tree limbs. No limbs larger than 4" in diameter or longer than 4' and no more than 1 pick-up truckload per house. Please call (270) 247-1981 if you have any questions.

post_text:
A Statement from Mayor Kathy O’Nan :
On the morning of July 10, 2020, it came to my attention that a political cartoon depicting violence against our president was shared by our official City of Mayfield Facebook Page to the Story Feed. Upon discovery, I immediately instructed the post be removed, and I conducted an internal inquiry into the matter. As a result of said inquiry, it was determined that a City employee had inadvertently shared the post using the City of Mayfield’s page to the City of Mayfield official page Story Feed. The determination that the post was shared as a result of inadvertence or mistake was made based upon consideration of all circumstances surrounding the incident. Appropriate disciplinary action will be taken against the employee in accordance with the City of Mayfield Employee Handbook. The City of Mayfield in no way condones the depictions displayed in the political cartoon shared, and the City of Mayfield offers sincere apologies to whomever the post offended. The employee has also apologized profusely.

Kentucky Office of Rural Health
May 20 at 6:55 AM ·

The Kentucky EMSC (Emergency Medical Services for Children Program) — which seeks to decrease pediatric mortality and morbidity due to severe illness or injury by enhancing pediatric emergency care services throughout the Commonwealth — recognized 12 rural EMS services earlier this year for meeting established criteria, beyond regulatory requirements, in order to improve capabilities to deliver care to pediatric patients.

Rural awardees included: Ballard County Ambulance Service, Bath County EMS, Pikeville Fire & EMS, Station 1, Georgetown/Scott County EMS, Hopkinsville Fire/EMS, Madison County EMS, Marshall County Ambulance Service, Mayfield Fire Department & Mayfield-Graves EMS, Montgomery County Fire/EMS, Murray Calloway Co. Ambulance, Somerset-Pulaski County EMS and Woodford County EMS KY. #EMSWeek2020 #EMSStrong

Mayfield Fire Department & Mayfield-Graves EMS
May 19 at 10:51 AM ·

National EMS Recognition Week- May 17-23, 2020

Thank you to the men and women who serve our community as the first link in the healthcare chain. Thank you for risking your lives so that another might live. Thank you for sacrificing so that others might benefit. Thank you for your professionalism, and thank you for your dedication. Thank you for always rising above the obstacles in front of us.

Thank you to each and every member of Mayfield Fire & EMS. This week we honor your role as EMS providers, but your role in our community goes much deeper than that. I can think of no finer group of providers, whether it be Fire, Rescue, or EMS response. The residents of Mayfield and Graves County are blessed to be served by this group of professionals, and it is my great honor to serve our community by serving alongside you.

Chief

post_text:
JUNE 2020 LIMB PICK-UP

The City of Mayfield’s Public Works Department has scheduled their next limb pick-up as follows:

Dividing Line-Broadway : June 1-4 South Side / June 8-11
North Side.

Please note that pick-up days have changed to Monday through Thursday. Neighborhoods from Erwin Drive going West to Old Dublin Road, place your limbs by the curb 48 hours prior to Monday, June 1, 2020.
Be aware that items cannot be placed by the curb for removal more than 48 hours before the scheduled pickup. No items may block a sidewalk. This pick-up program is intended for limbs only, not entire trees. If you have a tree trimmed or cut down by a contractor, it is your or their responsibility to remove the tree limbs, not the cities.
No limbs larger than 4” in diameter or longer than 4’, and no more than 1 pick-up truckload per house. Please call 247-1981 if you have any questions.

Legal notice
City of Mayfield
Proposed use hearing - Municipal Road Aid Funds

A public hearing will be held by the City of Mayfield at City Hall, 211 East Broadway, Mayfield KY on Monday May 11, 2020 at 5:30 pm. The purpose of the hearing is to obtain written or oral comments from citizens regarding possible use of Municipal Road Aid funds. All interested persons and organizations in the City of Mayfield are invited to the public hearing to submit comments on this subject. The use of funds is limited to the construction, maintenance of repair of city streets.
Due to COVID 19 this hearing will be held live via Facebook on the city’s Facebook page - City of Mayfield, Kentucky – City Hall.
Anyone who cannot attend the hearing may submit written comments to Public Works Department, Attn: Municipal Road Aid Fund, 211 East Broadway, Mayfield Ky 42066 or may call at 270-247-0067.

Governor Andy Beshear has released a phased Healthy at Work plan to reopen businesses. This plan is contingent upon no spike in new COVID-19 cases. Businesses must adhere to the guidelines listed below. The 10 rules to reopening a business under the Healthy at Work plan are:

Continue telework where possible
Phased return to work
Onsite temperature/health checks
Universal masks and other necessary PPE
Close common areas
Enforce social distancing
Limit face-to-face meetings
Sanitizer/hand wash stations
Special accommodations
Testing plan

These benchmarks closely follow the White House’s Guidelines for Reopening America.

post_text: Thanks to James D.Smith for this contribution to the safety and health of our first responders!
shared_text:
Mayfield Fire Department & Mayfield-Graves EMS
April 29 at 9:29 AM ·

Here is another great example of our wonderful community pulling together for the good of others.

James Smith Heating and Cooling approached the Mayfield Fire Department about donating a piece of equipment that would help with the decontamination process of our ambulances and personnel.

Besides owning and operating his HVAC business, James Smith is also the Fire Chief of Fancy Farm Volunteer Fire Department and a part time employee of the Mayfield-Graves County Ambulance Service. James recognized an opportunity to help out and donated an UV light air purifier to help keep our employees safe during DECON.

This act of kindness and generosity will keep our community safer by helping to ensure our personnel do not transport COVID-19 to our community if our services are requested.

Thank You James Smith Heating and Cooling.

April 7 at 3:33 PM ·

Mowing season is in full swing! We love the smell of freshly cut grass, but please be mindful not to blow or sweep clippings into the roadway. shared_text:
Mayfield Fire Department & Mayfield-Graves EMS
April 3 at 4:27 PM ·

Thank you to the Graves County Fiscal Court for approving the purchase of a UV light similar to what you see in the picture below. UV lights are proven to kill both viruses and bacteria. The light will be rotated between ambulances daily so that we can ensure a safer transport environment for our providers and patients. We were also able to purchase a handheld UV wand that can be used to sanitize PPE such as N95 masks. Less than 5 seconds of exposure to UV light from a distance of 2-3 inches is enough to kill any and all microbes on PPE. During a PPE crisis, reusing what we already have may be our only option. UV light technology can help us extend the life of what little supply we have on hand.

The lights were ordered yesterday, and we look forward to their delivery so we can immediately put them into use.

Misty Armstrong‎Mayfield “Bear Hunting” For The Kids
Admin · · 10 hrs ·

We were contacted and asked if we could start a story time for the local kids. In order to stay within acceptable social distancing guidelines we decided to do this in the form of videos! 💛
Each week on FRIDAY a local person will choose a book and record themselves reading the book. Then they’ll share that video with this page, Mayfield “Bear Hunting” For The Kids. 🙌🏼We would like to stay organized so please get with me if you’d like to read a book one week!

Next Friday Tracy Hargrove has chosen to read a book!! 🐻

Please allow your children to tune in and watch the video. 📗With school being out, we need to be sure our youth are actively reading and being read to. — with Tracy Hargrove, Tiffany Franklin, Jennifer Cavanaugh Wilson and Rudy Kellett.

post_text:
From the Office of the City Clerk:
Delinquent property taxes must be paid before March 31, 2020 to avoid publication and the tax sale. You may mail your payments to 211 E Broadway, Mayfield KY 42066 or go online to www.mayfieldky.gov – it is the green button at the bottom of the page. Please include a self-addressed stamped envelope if you pay by mail and wish to have a receipt.
The City of Mayfield business license with a renewal date of April 15, 2020 will now have a due date of July 15, 2020. We are honoring the new IRS tax due date therefore no penalties will be added. If you wish you may mail the renewals to 211 E Broadway, Mayfield KY 42066.
If you have any questions, we are in the office normal business hours, Monday thru Friday 8:00 to 4:30 pm. You may reach us by calling 270-247-1981.

Press Release
Office of the Mayor

March 17, 2020 (Mayfield KY) In accordance with recommendations of the Center for Disease Control, and in pursuance of the most recent guidance from the office of the Governor on March 17, 2020, and to promote the well-being of the citizens of Mayfield, City Hall will be closing to the public beginning at 8 a.m. on Thursday, March 19, 2020.
All city departments will remain responsive to our citizens’ needs through e-mail, the US Postal Service, and telephone @ (270) 247-1981. City Administrative employees will be available during regular business hours 8:00 a.m. – 4:30 p.m. All public parks will be closed and all scheduled events in the parks are cancelled.

Carr's Steakhouse
March 16 at 2:52 PM ·

As we are saddened to hear the decision to close restaurants and bars, we understand the Governor’s decision as we all do our part to flatten the curve.
As of today at 5pm we will change our hours and our approach to business and ceasing all dining room and bar service.
We will be open for delivery and curb side carry out from 11AM-7:30PM Monday- Thursday and 11AM-8PM Friday and Saturday. We will run full menu as long as supplies last. Please check on our Facebook for specials.
You can order online at https://direct.chownow.com/order/16068/locations/22814
Or give us a call 270-247-1111

As a reminder, we love our customers, we love our employees and trying our best as we navigate through these waters.

post_text:
Highlight of the March 9th Mayfield City Council meeting.
Mayor O’Nan welcomed a special guest to the council meeting. She first met Liam Sullivan on a visit to Northside Baptist Church to read to Liam’s 2nd Grade Class. Liam raised his hand and asked Mayor O’Nan if he could recite all the US President’s names to her. Mayor O’Nan was so impressed that she invited him to come and recite the President’s names to Mayfield City Council. Liam did a fine job and received a standing ovation. Great job young man! Pictured below Mayor O’Nan, Liam and his family - Liam Sullivan, Jay Sullivan, brother Jack Sullivan (7th Grade) and Valerie Stefanow.

post_text: Mr. Ben Saxton Sr. received the Outstanding Community Partner Award presented by Mayor Kathy O'Nan at Sunday's Black History Program at the First Church of the Nazarene. State Representative Charles Booker and State Representative Attica Scott of Kentucky House District 41 honored us with their presence. Mrs. Scott presented Mr. Ben Saxton Sr. with a Proclamation from the State. Mr. Saxton is an inspiration to all of us, a kind, loyal and hardworking gentleman. He is 91 years old and continues to work at Odom's Livestock on 45 South! Mr. Saxton, we wish you and your family all the best life has to offer. Photos by Joseph Petty.

ATTENTION! Please move your limbs as close to the curb/street as possible, do not pile them on the grass. The ground is saturated and we don't want to cause damage to your yard!

City-wide Limb Pickup 2020 (Dividing Line-Broadway)

March 2-5 South side / March 9-12 North side
June 1-4 South side / June 8-11 North side
September 14-17 South side / September 21-24 North Side

No limbs larger than 4” in diameter or longer than 4’;
Only 1 pick-up truck load per house;
Place items for pick-up by the curb no earlier than 48 hrs before scheduled pick-up;
Do not block sidewalks.

City-Wide Leaf Pick-up 2020 - December 7 - 10
If you have questions please call 270-251-6200.
